<script id="wix-first-paint">
    if (window.ResizeObserver &&
        (!window.PerformanceObserver || !PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes || PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes.indexOf('paint') === -1)) {
        new ResizeObserver(function (entries, observer) {
            entries.some(function (entry) {
                var contentRect = entry.contentRect;
                if (contentRect.width > 0 && contentRect.height > 0) {
                    requestAnimationFrame(function (now) {
                        window.wixFirstPaint = now;
                        dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('wixFirstPaint'));
                    });
                    observer.disconnect();
                    return true;
                }
            });
        }).observe(document.body);
    }
</script>

data-id="content-viewer"><div class="-RNAl"><div type="first" data-hook="rcv-block-first"></div><div class="Ll6Z5"><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-foo"><span class="f6nDn"><span>Deriving Threat Actor TTPs from Management Infrastructure Tracking</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block1"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-88llo"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W Sie1q"><div class="sDdA7" data-hook="divider divider-single"><div class="NVrgr"><svg class="tc33l VLo6m Bv6H9 fk8NK"><line x2="100%" y1="1" y2="1"></line></svg><div class="Jtym8"> </div></div></div></div></div></div><div type="divider" data-hook="rcv-block2"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7g2rf"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>You can find our previous work on </span></strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.team-cymru.com/post/a-visualizza-into-recent-icedid-campaigns" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Stage 1</span></strong></a><strong style="font-weight:700"><span> and </span></strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.team-cymru.com/post/tracking-bokbot-icedid-infrastructuremapping-a-vast-and-currently-active-icedid-network" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Stage 2</span></strong></a><strong style="font-weight:700"><span> of IcedID’s initial infection chain in our </span></strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.team-cymru.com/blog/categories/threat-research" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Dragons News Blog</span></strong></a><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>. Data on Stage 1 C2 infrastructure is now also shared as part of our Botnet Analysis and Reporting Service (</span></strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.team-cymru.com/malware-and-botnet-analysis-and-detection" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>BARS</span></strong></a><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>).</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block3"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-9inrj"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W Sie1q"><div class="sDdA7" data-hook="divider divider-single"><div class="NVrgr"><svg class="tc33l VLo6m Bv6H9 fk8NK"><line x2="100%" y1="1" y2="1"></line></svg><div class="Jtym8"> </div></div></div></div></div></div><div type="divider" data-hook="rcv-block4"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-58j8i"><span class="T1Eox"><span>As part of our ongoing tracking of IcedID / BokBot, we wanted to share some insights derived from infrastructure associated with IcedID’s BackConnect (BC) protocol. When deployed post “initial” compromise, the BC protocol allows the threat actor(s) additional functionality, using the infected host as a proxy.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block5"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1dv73"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block6"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-32iuf"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Amongst other things, the BC protocol contains a VNC module, providing the malware operator(s) with a remote-access channel which can be brokered for profit.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block7"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-55s8a"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block8"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6eoko"><span class="T1Eox"><span>For a comprehensive description of the BC protocol, we recommend </span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.netresec.com/?page=Blog&amp;month=2022-10&amp;post=IcedID-BackConnect-Protocol" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>this</span></a><span> blog by Netresec. Furthermore, we must credit </span><a target="_blank" href="https://twitter.com/malware_traffic" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>@malware_traffic</span></a><span> having drawn upon his collection of threat actor </span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.malware-traffic-analysis.net/index.html" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>telemetry data</span></a><span> to confirm some of the observations shared in this post.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block9"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7nn2e"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block10"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-75n4e"><span class="f6nDn"><span>Key Findings</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block11"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><ul class="mrVw3 soCUY"><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="f6O8Z" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="" id="viewer-hhv3"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Eleven BC C2s identified since 01 July 2022, managed via two VPN nodes.</span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="f6O8Z" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="" id="viewer-atda6"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Operators likely located in Moldova and Ukraine managing distinct elements of the BC protocol.</span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="f6O8Z" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="" id="viewer-a3eta"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Evidence of malicious use of the SpaceX Starlink network identified.</span></span></p></li><li dir="auto" aria-level="1" class="f6O8Z" style="text-align:AUTO;margin-inline-start:1.5em;list-style-type:disc"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="" id="viewer-2tf44"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Exposure of several tools and processes utilized by the operators, including temporary SMS messaging, file sharing, cryptocurrency wallets, and a favorite local radio station.</span></span></p></li></ul></div><div type="bulleted_list" data-hook="rcv-block12"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-e80ns"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block13"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-an2ba"><span class="f6nDn"><span>Starting Point - 51.89.201.236</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block14"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-144gp"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block15"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-e59j5"><span class="T1Eox"><span>The starting point for our analysis is derived from the two sources mentioned above; although not a new phenomenon, reporting on the BC protocol is fairly scarce, with the last major point of reference, prior to the most recent coverage, being made in </span><a target="_blank" href="https://blog.group-ib.com/icedid" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>May 2020</span></a><span>. </span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block16"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-8cs4p"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block17"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-9jqk8"><span class="T1Eox"><span>In early October 2022, an IOC (</span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>51.89.201.236</span></strong><span>:8080) derived from an IcedID infection was identified by </span><a target="_blank" href="https://twitter.com/malware_traffic" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>@malware_traffic</span></a><span>. The IOC was later attributed as a C2 server for the BC protocol by </span><a target="_blank" href="https://twitter.com/netresec" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>Netresec</span></a><span>, noting a change in the </span><em style="font-style:italic"><span>auth value</span></em><span> (0x08088b1f) used by the bot and C2 server for verification purposes.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block18"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" style="line-height:1.38" dir="auto" to identify two long standing management IP addresses, which were observed in communication with </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>11</span></strong><span> distinct BC C2 servers (including </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>51.89.201.236</span></strong><span>) since 01 July 2022.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block28"></div><div data-hook="rcv-block31"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-td9f"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block32"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-3ssq4"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Based on the data behind Figure 3, we can state that the average life cycle for a BC C2 server, based on first and last observations of management traffic, is approximately four weeks and that there are generally one or two servers active at any given time.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block33"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-8g2au"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block34"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fjlf6"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Additionally, in all cases communications between the C2 and management servers commenced and ceased on a Monday to Friday schedule - indicating a degree of “professionalism” to the operation and a point which became a trend during this analysis.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block35"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-2es12"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block36"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1gggt"><span class="f6nDn"><em style="font-style:italic"><span>Auth Value</span></em><span> Changes</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block37"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6ibkq"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block38"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-bma8j"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Returning to the aforementioned </span><em style="font-style:italic"><span>auth value</span></em><span> (0x08088b1f), based on our investigations, the campaigns involving </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>51.89.201.236</span></strong><span> are the first time the “new” auth value was observed. However, this finding is caveated with the fact that relevant PCAP data was not available for the two preceding C2 IPs - </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>135.125.242.223</span></strong><span> and </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>198.244.187.242</span></strong><span>. </span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block39"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-e7bjr"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block40"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6rne4"><span class="T1Eox"><span>All prior C2s used the “previous”</span><em style="font-style:italic"><span> auth value</span></em><span> (0x974f014a), which was associated with IcedID dating back a number of years. The change in </span><em style="font-style:italic"><span>auth value</span></em><span> therefore likely happened at some point between 30 August and 22 September 2022.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block41"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fej0j"><span class="T1Eox"><br style="font-size:14px"><span>135.181.175.108</span></span></strong><span style="font-size:14px"><span> (Last Active 30 August 2022)</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block44"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-f1ikh"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block45"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-c86bu"><span class="f6nDn"><span>Management Insights</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block46"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-9mkag"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block47"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fe9f5"><span class="T1Eox"><span>The remainder of this blog will focus on the two management IP addresses which have been associated with the operation of the BC protocol for at least half a year.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block48"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fa9va"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block49"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6ok61"><span class="T1Eox"><span>These IPs consistently connect to the BC C2 servers on the same two (separate) static ports, one which hosts a VNC service and the second which we hypothesize is associated with the SOCKS proxy module.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block50"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7mms5"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block51"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-cm88m"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W"><figure class="_2b-8D"><div role="button" data-hook="imageViewer" tabindex="0" class="EsRXE" aria-haspopup="true"><div style="--dim-height:745;--dim-width:1374" id="cm88m" class="_1xrgp Loyz9 UdkaQ"><wow-image id="747242_c5d6794a08b6437b8319c6efab5c5667~mv2.png" class="undefined UQr3P" data-image-info="{&quot;containerId&quot;:&quot;cm88m&quot;,&quot;displayMode&quot;:&quot;fill&quot;,&quot;isLQIP&quot;:true,&quot;isSEOBot&quot;:false,&quot;lqipTransition&quot;:&quot;blur&quot;,&quot;imageData&quot;:{&quot;width&quot;:1374,&quot;height&quot;:745,&quot;uri&quot;:&quot;747242_c5d6794a08b6437b8319c6efab5c5667~mv2.png&quot;,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;displayMode&quot;:&quot;fill&quot;}}" data-motion-part="BG_IMG" data-bg-effect-name="" data-has-ssr-src="true" data-animate-blur=""><img src="https://static.wixstatic.com/media/747242_c5d6794a08b6437b8319c6efab5c5667~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_auto/747242_c5d6794a08b6437b8319c6efab5c5667~mv2.png" alt="" style="width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:50% 50%;max-width:100%" data-pin-url="https://www.team-cymru.com/post/inside-the-icedid-backconnect-protocol" data-pin-media="https://static.wixstatic.com/media/747242_c5d6794a08b6437b8319c6efab5c5667~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_1374,h_745,al_c,q_90/747242_c5d6794a08b6437b8319c6efab5c5667~mv2.png" draggable="false"/></wow-image></div><div class="VsClR" role="button" tabindex="0"><svg viewBox="0 0 19 19" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="_99s9K"><path d="M15.071 8.371V4.585l-4.355 fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></div></div></figure></div></div></div><div type="image" data-hook="rcv-block52"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX uGQBe E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-am4kd"><span class="T1Eox"><span style="font-size:14px"><span>Figure 5: BackConnect Management</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block53"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-bjtuo"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block54"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fkoqi"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Setting the BC protocol management communications to one side, examining the rest of the data available for these two IP addresses provides an insight into the threat actor(s) operation, with some hints at attribution.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block55"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-ed9r6"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block56"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h4 class="lO0Ae yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-4qojc"><span class="f6nDn"><span>VNC Management</span></span></h4></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block57"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-8o23q"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block58"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-cujpm"><span class="T1Eox"><span>The first observation with the VNC Management is that it appears to be a VPN node. When examining inbound connections, a large proportion take place on UDP/1194, a port commonly associated with OpenVPN as the service’s default port.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block59"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-2iavr"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block60"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-29pv8"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>The VNC Management IP is therefore most likely used for routing traffic / providing anonymisation to the operator(s) and may not host any digital artifacts.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block61"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1gbe6"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block62"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-chcj9"><span class="T1Eox"><span>On the other side of the OpenVPN connections are numerous Moldovan IPs, the vast majority of which are assigned to a large residential broadband provider. In the 30-day period prior to the time of writing this report, 31 distinct Moldovan IPs were observed connecting to the VNC Management IP. Interestingly, the communications do not overlap, pointing towards a single user / access point.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block63"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7pu5f"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block64"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-8gggq"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Our hypothesis in this case is that the operator(s) of VNC Management IP are employing some operational security measures whilst operating from / via a residential access point. The data available points to an end user frequently rebooting their router in order to refresh their public IP address.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block65"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7hvl"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block66"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7dvsm"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Turning to outbound connections, a number of observations can be made, indicating potential operator TTPs.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block67"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-42kcn"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block68"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1a5vr"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Firstly, regular traffic to TeamViewer infrastructure was observed, indicating that the software may be installed on the operator’s machine, with usage routed through TeamViewer’s servers. Like VNC, TeamViewer has been used previously by threat actors for remote access management purposes, for example, it is leveraged to </span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.zdnet.com/article/following-oldsmar-attack-fbi-warns-about-using-teamviewer-and-windows-7/" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>gain access to networks</span></a><span> and </span><a target="_blank" href="https://www.mandiant.com/resources/blog/shining-a-light-on-darkside-ransomware-operations" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><span>establish persistence</span></a><span> in ransomware operations.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block69"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-9r1nt"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block70"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-3ofbv"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Secondly, communications with a single Tor relay were observed over an extended period. This particular finding may be indicative of a single operator accessing the Tor network via the VNC Management IP. </span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block71"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-31s9h"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block72"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1inro"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>By default, the Tor browser utilizes a small pool of Guard relays, which is refreshed approximately every 60 days. Ongoing communications with a single Tor relay is therefore indicative of an end user accessing Tor via the Tor browser. </span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block73"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-ds1qn"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block74"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7506b"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>As each instance of the Tor browser has its own set of Guard relays, multiple users accessing the Tor network via the same VPN access point would result in the observation of connections to multiple Tor relays.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block75"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-3eh2"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block76"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-24tlv"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W"><figure class="_2b-8D"><div role="button" data-hook="imageViewer" tabindex="0" class="EsRXE" aria-haspopup="true"><div style="--dim-height:552;--dim-width:1300" id="24tlv" class="_1xrgp Loyz9 UdkaQ"><wow-image id="747242_225fff6648324b4089536c47e34d95ab~mv2.png" class="undefined UQr3P" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></div></div></figure></div></div></div><div type="image" data-hook="rcv-block77"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX uGQBe E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-5gepu"><span class="T1Eox"><span style="font-size:14px"><span>Figure 6: Communications with Tor Relay</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block78"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-97sr2"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block79"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-f796o"><span class="T1Eox"><span>By examining the timeline of activity involving communications with this particular Tor relay, we can see that it was likely associated with the operator until 3 December 2022, when the Guard pool likely reset. Since this date we have not observed any further connections to Tor relays; likely as a result of a coverage gap.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block80"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6gr81"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block81"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-f77u3"><span class="T1Eox"><span>The majority of the Tor activity fits to a Monday to Friday schedule, although there were some days where access took place over the weekend. Most notably on 5 and 6 November 2022, following a spike in activity on 3 November 2022.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block82"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-99c7m"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block83"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-a3lfd"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>This activity coincided with a resurgence of Emotet activity, which included a </span></strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.proofpoint.com/uk/blog/threat-insight/comprehensive-look-emotets-fall-2022-return" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>new version of IcedID</span></strong></a><strong style="font-weight:700"><span> being dropped alongside it. The spike is therefore a possible indicator of collusion between the operators of Emotet and IcedID.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block84"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6febc"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block85"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-27v5v"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Aside from Tor, connections were also observed to IPs assigned to Telegram, indicating likely use of Telegram messenger. This finding is not particularly exciting (Telegram is used widely), but serves to highlight the overall TTPs of the VNC Management IP operators.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block86"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-a8ie7"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block87"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-84kbt"><span class="T1Eox"><span>More interestingly, traffic to </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>onlinesim[.]ru</span></strong><span> caught our attention. This website appears to provide temporary ‘virtual’ numbers to be used for sending / receiving SMS messages.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block88"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fq45p"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block89"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7dk6"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>By virtue of the fact that this domain was accessed via the same infrastructure as is used to manage the BC C2s, it can be inferred that these temporary numbers serve a purpose in the overall process; although the exact use-case is currently unknown.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block90"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-c1ahq"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block91"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-68v0h"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Another indicator for operator attribution came in the form of connections to an API for a local radio station based in Chelyabinsk, Central Russia.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block92"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6h10b"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block93"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-61k5a"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>We have two hypotheses for this activity, a) the API is embedded in another website and is pulling data from the radio station in Chelyabinsk, or b) the operator has some ties to that particular region of Russia; an expat living in Moldova?</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block94"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-573jm"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block95"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-15fa6"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Finally, we observed RDP connections to a set of IPs that share a distinct machine name, however it is unclear what the purpose of these connections are beyond the obvious use of the RDP protocol.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block96"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-hnvi"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block97"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-7ing0"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W"><figure class="_2b-8D"><div role="button" data-hook="imageViewer" tabindex="0" class="EsRXE" aria-haspopup="true"><div style="--dim-height:985;--dim-width:1283" id="7ing0" class="_1xrgp Loyz9 UdkaQ"><wow-image src="https://static.wixstatic.com/media/747242_ed64f50a5f284126aa42791eee740946~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_38,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_auto/747242_ed64f50a5f284126aa42791eee740946~mv2.png" alt="" style="width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:50% 50%;max-width:100%" data-pin-url="https://www.team-cymru.com/post/inside-the-icedid-backconnect-protocol" data-pin-media="https://static.wixstatic.com/media/747242_ed64f50a5f284126aa42791eee740946~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_1283,h_985,al_c,q_90/747242_ed64f50a5f284126aa42791eee740946~mv2.png" draggable="false"/></wow-image></div><div class="VsClR" role="button" tabindex="0"><svg viewBox="0 0 19 19" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="_99s9K"><path d="M15.071 8.371V4.585l-4.355 4.356a.2.2 0 0 1-.283 0l-.374-.374a.2.2 0 0 1 0-.283l4.356-4.355h-3.786a.2.2 0 0 1-.2-.2V3.2c0-.11.09-.2.2-.2H16v5.371a.2.2 0 0 1-.2.2h-.529a.2.2 0 0 1-.2-.2zm-6.5 6.9v.529a.2.2 0 0 1-.2.2H3v-5.371c0-.11.09-.2.2-.2h.529c.11 0 .2.09.2.2v3.786l4.355-4.356a.2.2 0 0 1 .283 0l.374.374a.2.2 0 0 1 0 .283L4.585 15.07h3.786c.11 0 .2.09.2.2z" fill="#000" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></div></div></figure></div></div></div><div type="image" data-hook="rcv-block98"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX uGQBe E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-cu7ut"><span class="T1Eox"><span style="font-size:14px"><span>Figure 7: Summary of Activity - VNC Management IP</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block99"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-8n74h"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block100"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h4 class="lO0Ae yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-35i7d"><span class="f6nDn"><span>SOCKS Management</span></span></h4></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block101"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-2l356"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block102"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-2uihi"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Intriguingly, although the SOCKS Management IP serves a similar purpose to the VNC Management IP, there are variations in both how this is accomplished and by whom.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block103"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1rfaj"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block104"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-46ugf"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Like the VNC Management IP, the SOCKS Management IP appears to be a VPN node, masking the true location of the operator(s), used to funnel not only BC protocol-related communications, but also other (mostly) connected activities.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block105"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1ite2"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block106"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-8i29j"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Inbound traffic to the SOCKS Management IP is observed over UDP/51820, the default port for the open-source WireGuard VPN service.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block107"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-dnafg"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block108"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-ev8ir"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Noting the similar use of an (albeit different) open-source, and likely private, VPN service.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block109"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-5sp9m"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block110"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-3vabj"><span class="T1Eox"><span>On the other end of these communications are a handful of IPs assigned to providers in Ukraine. Most significantly, several of these IPs are attributable to ‘SpaceX Starlink’ infrastructure provided to Ukraine to help maintain Internet connectivity since the commencement of Russia’s “special operation” / illegal invasion in February 2022.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block111"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-5kogi"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block112"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-nekh"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>It is possible that this is the first example of the Starlink infrastructure being used by cyber criminals.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block113"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-el3n3"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block114"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-39lig"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Beyond the Ukrainian IPs, in this case it is difficult to attribute the management activity more specifically; as the infrastructure is likely utilized by tens, or even hundreds of users at any given time.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block115"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-e516i"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block116"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-11onh"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W"><figure class="_2b-8D"><div role="button" data-hook="imageViewer" tabindex="0" class="EsRXE" aria-haspopup="true"><div style="--dim-height:490;--dim-width:1911" id="11onh" class="_1xrgp Loyz9 UdkaQ"><wow-image id="747242_3249820e18e7464480fd8872b4989443~mv2.png" class="undefined UQr3P" data-image-info="{&quot;containerId&quot;:&quot;11onh&quot;,&quot;displayMode&quot;:&quot;fill&quot;,&quot;isLQIP&quot;:true,&quot;isSEOBot&quot;:false,&quot;lqipTransition&quot;:&quot;blur&quot;,&quot;imageData&quot;:{&quot;width&quot;:1911,&quot;height&quot;:490,&quot;uri&quot;:&quot;747242_3249820e18e7464480fd8872b4989443~mv2.png&quot;,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;displayMode&quot;:&quot;fill&quot;}}" 1-.2.2H3v-5.371c0-.11.09-.2.2-.2h.529c.11 0 .2.09.2.2v3.786l4.355-4.356a.2.2 0 0 1 .283 0l.374.374a.2.2 0 0 1 0 .283L4.585 15.07h3.786c.11 0 .2.09.2.2z" fill="#000" fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></div></div></figure></div></div></div><div type="image" data-hook="rcv-block117"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX uGQBe E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1d288"><span class="T1Eox"><span style="font-size:14px"><span>Figure 8: Inbound and Outbound Activity - SOCKS Management IP</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block118"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-cq6mt"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block119"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7jkre"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Looking at outbound connections from the SOCKS Management IP, there is similar use of Tor and Telegram. Although, in the case of Tor, this may be more indicative of some form of automated or hidden service-related activity as communications with numerous Tor relays were observed.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block120"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-e03tq"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block121"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-5llsu"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>This is in comparison with the VNC Management IP which appeared to only communicate with the one Tor relay; matching more closely the ‘expected’ behavior of an individual using the Tor browser.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block122"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-ciegk"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block123"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6ep69"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Additionally, a large volume of connections, both inbound and outbound, over TCP and UDP/33445 were observed, generally associated with Tox messenger.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block124"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-52iut"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block125"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-9td0v"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Tox has been utilized by cyber criminals in the past, including for C2 purposes. The default port for Tox is UDP/33445, however mobile connections default to TCP - it is therefore possible that the operator(s) of the SOCKS Management IP are using it to access Tox on both desktop and mobile.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block126"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-a3ads"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block127"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-bb38s"><span class="T1Eox"><span>In much the same way as the BC C2s have a life cycle of around four weeks, the SOCKS Management IP also communicates with cloud infrastructure (accessed via SSH) with the cloud peer IP changing over time. However, it was noted that all of the cloud IPs displayed the same unique SSH Server Host Key, indicating a likely consistent setup.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block128"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-4j130"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block129"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-32fcb"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Finally, looking at outbound web-browsing activity (TCP/80 and TCP/443), the SOCKS Management IP is used to access IP addresses associated with Gofile (file sharing), ProtonMail, Trezor (cryptocurrency wallet), and a not insignificant number of pornographic sites (someone in IcedID senior management needs to crack down on adherence to the Acceptable Use Policy!).</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block130"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-e5ir"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block131"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="eqS3g" id="viewer-egf00"><div class="_5Llbo kIU8W"><figure class="_2b-8D"><div role="button" data-hook="imageViewer" tabindex="0" class="EsRXE" aria-haspopup="true"><div style="--dim-height:999;--dim-width:1364" id="egf00" class="_1xrgp Loyz9 UdkaQ"><wow-image id="747242_ea9a330e1bcd4d6e805a37dc6af62af3~mv2.png" class="undefined UQr3P" data-image-info="{&quot;containerId&quot;:&quot;egf00&quot;,&quot;displayMode&quot;:&quot;fill&quot;,&quot;isLQIP&quot;:true,&quot;isSEOBot&quot;:false,&quot;lqipTransition&quot;:&quot;blur&quot;,&quot;imageData&quot;:{&quot;width&quot;:1364,&quot;height&quot;:999,&quot;uri&quot;:&quot;747242_ea9a330e1bcd4d6e805a37dc6af62af3~mv2.png&quot;,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;displayMode&quot;:&quot;fill&quot;}}" data-motion-part="BG_IMG" data-bg-effect-name="" data-has-ssr-src="true" data-animate-blur=""><img src="https://static.wixstatic.com/media/747242_ea9a330e1bcd4d6e805a37dc6af62af3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_36,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_auto/747242_ea9a330e1bcd4d6e805a37dc6af62af3~mv2.png" alt="" style="width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:50% 50%;max-width:100%" data-pin-url="https://www.team-cymru.com/post/inside-the-icedid-backconnect-protocol" data-pin-media="https://static.wixstatic.com/media/747242_ea9a330e1bcd4d6e805a37dc6af62af3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_1364,h_999,al_c,q_90/747242_ea9a330e1bcd4d6e805a37dc6af62af3~mv2.png" draggable="false"/></wow-image></div><div class="VsClR" role="button" tabindex="0"><svg viewBox="0 0 19 19" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="_99s9K"><path d="M15.071 8.371V4.585l-4.355 fill-rule="nonzero"></path></svg></div></div></figure></div></div></div><div type="image" data-hook="rcv-block132"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX uGQBe E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1vivh"><span class="T1Eox"><span style="font-size:14px"><span>Figure 9: Summary of Activity - SOCKS Management IP</span></span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block133"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-cpomg"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block134"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-2k719"><span class="f6nDn"><span>Conclusion</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block135"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1984b"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block136"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-ckbuv"><span class="T1Eox"><span>This blog serves two purposes, the first is to highlight our tracking of BC C2 infrastructure, sharing details of C2 servers and the process we undertake behind the scenes in order to identify them.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block137"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-2lvhu"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block138"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-d3hhi"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>We will continue to share details of new / emerging BC C2 servers via our Twitter account </span></strong><a target="_blank" href="https://twitter.com/teamcymru_S2" rel="noopener" class="rJEfu fP51A" data-hook="WebLink"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>@teamcymru_S2</span></strong></a><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block139"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-c8gj0"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block140"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-27p74"><span class="T1Eox"><span>The second is to provide a snapshot into a ‘day in the life of’ the BC operators, and in doing so, providing wider context on threat actor TTPs.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block141"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-ae5nk"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block142"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-b7iis"><span class="T1Eox"><span>In the case of BC, there appears to be two operators managing the overall process within distinct roles. Much of the activity we observe and have described in this blog occurs during the typical working week (Monday to Friday).</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block143"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7godu"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block144"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-591gn"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Both of these points indicate a degree of ‘professionalism’ in the operation of the BC protocol, and by extension IcedID itself.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block145"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-bqq3j"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block146"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fl2ks"><span class="T1Eox"><span>Evidence of a ‘dispersed’ workforce undertaking specific tasks may also help to explain some of the variations in the TTPs observed. Whilst seemingly using two distinct VPN services, we can see an overall ‘playbook’ in use, i.e., its best practice to use a VPN for purposes of anonymization. The fact that both services are configured with default settings indicate either laziness, attempts to ‘hide within the noise’, or a lack of understanding / appreciation of the tooling in use.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block147"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fqo0t"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block148"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1dk98"><span class="T1Eox"><span>We were surprised that beyond the use of a VPN node, very few steps appear to have been taken to cover the operators’ tracks; we think this speaks to a confidence in ‘invincibility’, by operating from regions where law enforcement action is difficult to effect / prioritize.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block149"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-b3pvs"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block150"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-agv96"><span class="T1Eox"><span>The use of services like ProtonMail, TeamViewer and Telegram is commonly observed within threat actor operator playbooks, and these mainstream tools continue to be used by maliciously motivated individuals. Services like Gofile and </span><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>onlinesim[.]ru</span></strong><span> may point to more ‘operator-specific’ TTPs, whilst also highlighting a general use of file sharing and temporary SMS platforms.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block151"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-7fg3s"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block152"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-6p19h"><span class="T1Eox"><strong style="font-weight:700"><span>Finally, by highlighting a number of areas where we still have question marks in our understanding, we hope that we can encourage future collaboration on the BC protocol.</span></strong></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block153"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-1uos8"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block154"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><p class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-dp3kr"><span class="T1Eox"><span>We hope that this blog post has been informative and has served to provide confidence in the IOCs which we have previously shared on this subject matter.</span></span></p></div><div type="paragraph" data-hook="rcv-block155"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-3ll6n"><span class="T1Eox"><br role="presentation"/></span></div></div><div type="empty-line" data-hook="rcv-block156"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><h3 class="_8J6VB yelXh soCUY E8vnw" dir="auto" id="viewer-fur0f"><span class="f6nDn"><span>IOCs</span></span></h3></div><div type="heading" data-hook="rcv-block157"></div><div data-breakout="normal"><div class="SFG-K RJWgX soCUY E8vnw"
